    "opinion": "As a 21-year-old student from Bari who spends about an hour daily on social media, I approach the issue of fake content with a practical mindset shaped by my background and values. Growing up in Italy with Christian beliefs, I value truth and community, which makes me particularly concerned about how misinformation can harm social bonds. My moderate neuroticism means I do worry about the emotional impact of fake content, especially when it spreads fear or division among people I care about. However, my high agreeableness drives me to seek solutions that foster understanding rather than conflict. Managing fake content starts with personal responsibility. Given my limited time online, I focus on being selective about what I engage with. I check sources before sharing anything, often looking for reputable news outlets or official statements, as I believe this aligns with my conscientious effort to avoid spreading falsehoods. My hobbies like hiking and painting keep me grounded in reality, reminding me that not everything online reflects the truth of the world. I also think social media platforms should play a stronger role. They could implement clearer labeling for unverified content and promote educational tools to help users like me, who are not tech experts, spot misinformation. As a student, I appreciate learning opportunities, so I support initiatives that teach digital literacy in schools or through community programs in Bari. My parents' varied educational backgrounds—one with no formal education and the other with a vocational diploma—have taught me the importance of accessible information, so I advocate for solutions that don't exclude people based on their knowledge level. Ultimately, dealing with fake content requires a balanced approach: being vigilant without becoming paranoid, and encouraging others to do the same through gentle reminders rather than confrontation. This way, we can protect our mental health and maintain the trust that holds our communities together.",
